===2009&ndash;11: ''Next Level'', ''Rock n Roll Circus'' and ''Five''===
Hamasaki's next two singles, "[[Days/Green]]" (December 2008) and "[[Rule/Sparkle]]" (February 2009), continued Hamasaki's streak of number-one singles. "Rule" is used as the international theme song for the film ''[[Dragonball Evolution]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/081210/gnj0812100505015-n2.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5cwz18FdO?url=http://www.sanspo.com/geino/news/081210/gnj0812100505015-n2.htm |archivedate=December 10, 2008 |title=Ayu to Sing the International Theme Song of Dragonball |work=[[Sankei Sports]] |publisher=Sankei Digital Inc. |accessdate=December 10, 2008 |date=December 10, 2008 |page=2 |language=ja |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref> The subsequent studio album, ''[[Next Level (Ayumi Hamasaki album)|Next Level]]'', was released on March 25, 2009 in several formats: CD, CD+DVD, 2CD+DVD and a two-[[gigabyte]] [[USB flash drive]].<ref name=USB>{{cite web |url=http://www.sponichi.co.jp/entertainment/news/2009/02/13/04.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5eXxRHxKn?url=http://www.sponichi.co.jp/entertainment/news/2009/02/13/04.html |archivedate=February 13, 2009 |title=Ayu's USB album |publisher=Sponichi Annex |accessdate=February 12, 2009 |language=ja |deadurl=yes |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/news/090212.html|title=Ayumi Hamasaki official website news and information|publisher=[[Avex]]|accessdate=February 13, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090214224145/http://avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/news/090212.html| archivedate= February 14, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no|language=ja}}</ref> Sonically, ''Next Level'' was mainly an [[electronic dance music|electronic dance]] album.<ref>{{cite web|last=Greenberg|first=Adam|title=Next Level|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1557845|pure_url=yes}}|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=September 2, 2010}}</ref> ''Next Level'' reached the top of the Oricon charts, making Hamasaki the only artist to have a number-one album every year for eleven years in a row since her debut.<ref name="nextlevel" /> However, the album was only certified [[Recording Industry Association of Japan#Criteria|double platinum]], making it Hamasaki's lowest-selling studio album to that date.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/data/others/gold/200903.html|title=Gold-Certified Works of March 2009|publisher=RIAJ|accessdate=May 14, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090505201529/http://www.riaj.or.jp/data/others/gold/200903.html| archivedate= May 5, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no|language=ja}}</ref> On August 12, 2009, Hamasaki released her forty-sixth single, "[[Sunrise/Sunset (Love Is All)]]". "Sunrise (Love Is All)", one of the [[A-side]]s, is being used as the opening theme song for the [[Japanese television drama]] ''Dandy Daddy?''.<ref name="June 30, 2009">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/music/67305/full/|title=Ayumi Hamasaki, to sing first drama theme song in six years|publisher=[[Oricon]]|accessdate=July 2, 2009}}</ref> The single reached the top of the weekly charts, making it her twenty-first consecutive (thirty-third total) number-one single. "Sunrise/Sunset" is also her forty-fourth single to enter the Top 10, making Hamasaki the artist with the most Top 10 singles ever.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/rankmusic/68479/|title=Ayumi Hamasaki Has the Most Top 10 Singles in History, with 44 Titles|publisher=[[Oricon]]|accessdate=April 3, 2010|date=August 18, 2009|language=ja}}</ref> Hamasaki's third single of the year, "[[You Were.../Ballad]]", was released on December 29, 2009. Hamasaki's eleventh studio album ''[[Rock 'n' Roll Circus]]'' was released on April 14, 2010. Though the album contained a few "powerful and melodramatic gothic rock" tracks, it was mainly "pure and classic J-pop", with pop-rock songs and ballads.<ref>{{cite web|last=Eremenko|first=Alexey|title=Rock'n'Roll Circus|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1813626|pure_url=yes}}|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=September 2, 2010}}</ref> The album topped the charts, making Hamasaki the first female solo artist in twenty years to have ten number-one original studio albums.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/confidence/75496/ | title=Hamasaki Ayumi's Tenth Number-One Original Album | publisher=[[Oricon]] | language=Japanese | accessdate=April 20, 2010}}</ref> Hamasaki also began expanding her online presence, setting up accounts on MySpace, [[Ustream]], and Twitter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://music.jp.msn.com/news/article.aspx?articleid=266772 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5p96xPnoC?url=http://music.jp.msn.com/news/article.aspx?articleid=266772 |archivedate=April 21, 2010 |title=Hamasaki Ayumi, One New Web Experiment After Another |publisher=MSN |date=April 13, 2010 |accessdate=April 20, 2010 |language=ja |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://house.sina.com.cn/overseas/japan/2010-04-15/1823342615.html|title=Hamasaki Ayumi Tries an Experiment on the Internet|publisher=[[SINA Corporation]]|work=[[Sina.com]]|accessdate=April 20, 2010|date=April 15, 2010|language=zh|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720022310/http://house.sina.com.cn/overseas/japan/2010-04-15/1823342615.html|archivedate=July 20, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In July, entertainment company Livespire announced that Hamasaki's [[Ayumi Hamasaki Arena Tour 2009 A: Next Level|2009 ''Next Level'' tour]] would be [[3D film|shown in 3D]] at Toho cinemas nationwide beginning on August 28.<ref>{{cite web|title=2010 News |url=http://livespire.jp/movie/a3d.html |work=Livespire.jp |publisher=[[Sony Corporation]] |accessdate=August 6, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818200506/http://livespire.jp/movie/a3d.html |archivedate=August 18, 2010 |deadurl=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Release Information: A3D ayumi hamasaki ARENA TOUR 2009 A ～NEXT LEVEL～ |url=http://www.livespire.jp/movie/a3d.html |work=Livespire.jp |publisher=[[Sony Corporation]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818200506/http://livespire.jp/movie/a3d.html |archivedate=August 18, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Screening Information Schedule & Theater: A3D ayumi hamasaki ARENA TOUR 2009 A ～NEXT LEVEL～|url=http://www.livespire.jp/schedule/a3d.html|work=Livespire.jp|publisher=[[Sony Corporation]]|accessdate=August 6, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818195155/http://www.livespire.jp/schedule/a3d.html|archivedate=August 18, 2010|deadurl=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

On July 14, Hamasaki released her forty-eighth single, "[[Moon/Blossom]]". The single was released as the first of a three-part project to celebrate her yet-unreleased fiftieth single.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/news/100520a.html | title=July 14 (Wednesday) New Single 'Moon/Blossom' [and] 'Blossom/Moon' | work=Ayumi Hamasaki Official Website | publisher=[[Avex]] | language=Japanese | accessdate=August 18, 2010}}</ref> The two other singles in the project (her forty-ninth and fiftieth singles respectively), "[[Crossroad (song)|Crossroad]]" and "[[L (Ayumi Hamasaki EP)|L]]", were released within a week of each other, "Crossroad" on September 22 and "L" on September 29.<ref name="August 6, 2010">{{cite web | url=http://www.avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/news/100806.html | title=Two-Week Consecutive Release of 49th, 50th Singles Set！ | work=Ayumi Hamasaki Official Website | publisher=[[Avex]] | language=Japanese | accessdate=August 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100816102528/http://www.avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/news/100806.html| archivedate= August 16, 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> "Crossroad" was composed by [[Tetsuya Komuro]] and its coupling was her cover version of Komuro's band [[TM Network]]'s 1988 song "Seven Days War", which was her first cover of a male song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/music/79599/full/|title=Ayu Covers a Male Song for the First Time on Her New Work|publisher=[[Oricon]]|language=Japanese|date=August 31, 2010|accessdate=September 23, 2010}}</ref> The three singles all topped the Oricon, becoming Hamasaki's twenty-third, twenty-fourth and twenty-fifth consecutive number-one singles and setting a new record for the most consecutive number-one singles by any female artist (solo or group) as well as by any solo artist.<ref name="record" /> On December 22, Hamasaki released her twelfth original studio album, ''[[Love Songs (Ayumi Hamasaki album)|Love Songs]]''. On the same day, Naoya Urata of [[AAA (band)|AAA]] released his debut solo single "[[Dream On (Naoya Urata song)|Dream On]]". The song, which featured Hamasaki, was written and produced by her as well, marking the first record she produced for another singer.<ref>{{zh-tw icon}} {{cite news|url=http://udn.com/NEWS/ENTERTAINMENT/ENT5/6025285.shtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101211152426/http://udn.com/NEWS/ENTERTAINMENT/ENT5/6025285.shtml |dead-url=yes |archive-date=December 11, 2010 |title=Hamasaki [Assists] in Pupil Urata Naoya's Debut |accessdate=December 31, 2010 |language=Chinese |date=December 10, 2010 |publisher=UDN Group |df= }}</ref> ''Love Songs'' and "Dream On" both reached the top spots on their respective Oricon charts. ''Love Songs'' became Hamasaki's fourth consecutive and seventeenth total number-one album. The album also marked Hamasaki's thirteenth consecutive year with a number-one album, breaking her old record.<ref name="Hamasaki Ayumi's new album & collaboration single top Oricon">{{cite web | url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/rankmusic/83429/full/|title=Ayumi Hamasaki, the First [Person] to Have a Number-One Album for 13 Consecutive Years|publisher=[[Oricon]]|work=Oricon Style|accessdate=February 22, 2011|date=December 28, 2010|language=ja}}</ref>

In February 2011, it was announced that her arena tour of the year, ''Hotel Love Songs'', would start in April. Shortly after the [[2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami|2011 Tohoku earthquake and tsunami]] hit, it was announced that the tour was rescheduled to start in late May and the tour was renamed to ''Power of Music''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/schedule/index.html#live |title=SCHEDULE – ayumi hamasaki(浜崎あゆみ) official website |publisher=Avexnet.or.jp |accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> Deeply affected by the Tohoku earthquake and tsunami devastation, Hamasaki decided to collaborate with fashion magazine, ''Vivi'', with the sale of charity shirts and the profits going to help the victims in the devastation. On April 20, 2011, Hamasaki simultaneously released four new remix albums, ''Ayu-mi-x 7'':''[[Ayu-mi-x 7 Version House|House]]'', ''[[Ayu-mi-x 7 Version Acoustic Orchestra|Acoustic Orchestra]]'', ''[[Ayu-mi-x 7 Presents Ayu Trance 4|Trance 4]]'', ''[[Ayu-mi-x 7 Presents Ayu-ro Mix 4|Ayu-ro Mix 4]]'', and a ''[[Ayu-mi-x 7 Limited Complete Box Set|Limited Complete Box Set]]'', which were also released internationally on [[iTunes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/news/110420.html |title=NEWS&INFORMATION – ayumi hamasaki(浜崎あゆみ) official website |publisher=Avexnet.or.jp |accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> On that same day, Hamasaki also released ''[[Rock'n'Roll Circus Tour Final: 7days Special|2010 Rock 'n' Roll Circus Tour]]'' and ''[[A 50 Singles: Live Selection]]'' which topped the weekly chart at No. 1 and No. 2 respectively. The simultaneous releases made Hamasaki the first artist ever to have 4 albums in Oricon's top 10 and also the first artist to hold 2 top positions in the Oricon DVD chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20110426-00000330-oric-musi |title=浜崎あゆみ、史上初のアルバム4作同時TOP10入り|date=April 27, 2011|language=Japanese|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430103230/http://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20110426-00000330-oric-musi|archivedate=April 30, 2011|deadurl=yes|publisher=Oricon}}</ref> Their original release date of March 30 was postponed due to the 2011 Tohoku earthquake and tsunami and was pushed back to April 20 instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/news/index.html |title=NEWS&INFORMATION – ayumi hamasaki(浜崎あゆみ) official website |publisher=Avexnet.or.jp |accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> On April 21, 2011, it was announced that she would perform in a-nation 10th Anniversary for Life Charge & Go!<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/news/110421.html |title=NEWS&INFORMATION – ayumi hamasaki(浜崎あゆみ) official website |publisher=Avexnet.or.jp |accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> On May 4, it was announced that she broke another record – the female artist with the highest DVD sales with 2,313,000.<ref>{{cite web|author=2011年05月04日 04時00分 |url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/confidence/87335/ |title=浜崎あゆみ、音楽DVD総売上で女性アーティスト首位に ニュース-ORICON STYLE |publisher=Oricon.co.jp |accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref>

On August 31, Hamasaki released her second mini album ''[[Five (EP)|Five]]'', her first since ''[[Memorial Address]]'' in 2003. This is her first album to have no singles released. ''[[Five (EP)|Five]]'' topped the [[Oricon Charts]] for 2 consecutive weeks, her first to do so since ''[[(Miss)understood]]''. The lead song, "Progress", was used as a theme song for the videogame, ''[[Tales of Xillia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/2010/12/ayumi-hamasaki-to-sing-theme-song-for-ps3-game-tales-of-xillia |title=Ayumi Hamasaki to sing theme song for "Tales of Xillia"! |publisher=Tokyohive.com |date=2010-12-30 |accessdate=2012-12-30}}</ref> The album also features collaborations, with singers [[Juno (singer)|Juno]] and Naoya Urata from [[AAA (band)|AAA]]. This album managed to be certified Gold by [[RIAJ]], making Hamasaki's first album not to be certified Platinum.<ref name="RIAJ">{{cite web | url = http://www.riaj.or.jp/e/index.html | title = Recording Industry Association of Japan | publisher = [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]]}}</ref> ''Complete Clip Box 1998–2011'', consisting all her music videos from her first single, "Poker Face" till her latest mini-album, ''Five'', was released on January 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/news/111117.html | title = 2012年1月1日(日)発売DVD ＆ Blu-ray BOX『 CLIP BOX 1998–2011(仮)』の TeamAyu＆mu-moショップオリジナル特典付き販売決定}}</ref> "How Beautiful You Are" will be the theme song for a drama ''[[Saigo Kara Nibanme no Koi]]'', and also Hamasaki's second digital single (55th single overall), which is released fully on February 8.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.avexnet.or.jp/ayu/jp/news/120201.html | title = Theme Song 「最後から二番目の恋」released as a single on 2/8!}}</ref> Hamasaki describe the song as a mid-tempo ballad and a feeling of gratitude towards someone.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.jpopasia.com/news/ayumi-hamasaki-sings-theme-song-for-upcoming-drama::9633.html | title = Ayumi Hamasaki Sings Theme Song for Upcoming Drama}}</ref>

===2012&ndash;13: 15th anniversary, ''Love Again'' and compilation releases===
In 2012, The International 3D Society announced the winners of its 2012 3D Creative Arts Awards with Hamasaki receiving an award for "Electronic Broadcast Media (Television) – Live Event" for her ''A3D ayumi hamasaki Arena Tour 2009 A (Next Level)'' tour.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hugo-martin-scorsese-3D-society-awards-286469 |title='Hugo' Tops International 3D Society Awards With Three Trophies |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |date=November 17, 2011 |accessdate=February 18, 2012 |first=Carolyn |last=Giardina}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpopasia.com/news/ayumi-hamasaki-wins-award-at-international-3d-awards::10040.html |title=Ayumi Hamasaki Wins Award At International 3D Awards |publisher=Jpopasia.com |date=February 10, 2012 |accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref> On March 21, Hamasaki released her thirteenth studio album, ''[[Party Queen]]''. The album peaked at number two on the Oricon charts, becoming her second studio album to do so after 2007's ''Guilty''. On August 6, 2012, Hamasaki released her sixth compilation album ''[[A Summer Best]]''. It included two new songs which were digitally released for the promotion of the album: the [[TRF (band)|TRF]] cover, ''[[Happening Here]]'', and ''You & Me''.

In September 2012, it was announced that, to commemorate Hamasaki's 15th anniversary in the music industry on April 8, 2013, she would be releasing new material for five consecutive months starting on the 8th day of November, 2012, until the 8th of March, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:浜崎あゆみ、「毎月8日」に5ヶ月連続新作発表|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2017090/full/|publisher=Oricon Style|accessdate=15 June 2014|language=Japanese}}</ref> The first releases were two mini albums, ''[[Love (Ayumi Hamasaki album)|Love]]'' and ''[[Again (Ayumi Hamasaki album)|Again]]'', which were put on sale on the 8th of November and December, respectively. The third release for the 8th of January was her compilation album ''[[A Classical]]'', which included classical arrangements of previously released songs. The fourth release was Hamasaki's 14th studio album, ''[[Love Again (Ayumi Hamasaki album)|Love Again]]'', which compiled the songs included in the two previous mini albums. And finally the fifth was the DVD/Blu-ray of her ''Arena Tour 2012: Hotel Love Songs'', released in March.<ref>{{cite web|title=浜崎あゆみ 5ヶ月連続リリース記念特集|url=http://shop.mu-mo.net/a/st/event/ayu1211/|website=mu-mo Shop|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>　In April 2013 Hamasaki began her ''15th Anniversary Tour: A Best Live'', which lasted for four months until the end of July. Its setlist was chosen by fans through online voting, and was later released as her first [[live album]] CD on September 18.<ref name="first live album">{{cite web|title=アルバム連続TOP10歴代1位を獲得した浜崎あゆみ|url=http://news.merumo.ne.jp/article/genre/1678577|publisher=Yomerumo News|accessdate=15 June 2014|language=Japanese}}</ref> The DVD and Blu-ray versions were released on October 30, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=浜崎あゆみ、大好評開催中の15周年記念アリーナツアーが早くもLIVE CD＆LIVE DVD/Blu-rayで発売決定！さらに、ライヴ会場にてご予約頂くと"当日のLIVE音源"を終演後にダウンロードプレゼント！！|url=http://avex.jp/ayu/news/detail.php?id=1002824|publisher=Ayumi Hamasaki Official website|accessdate=15 June 2014|language=Japanese}}</ref> On December 25, 2013, Hamasaki released "[[Feel the love / Merry-go-round|Feel the Love/Merry-go-round]]", her first physical single in three years. "Feel the Love" was composed by [[Tetsuya Komuro]] and produced by Dj Hello Kitty, while "Merry-go-round" was produced by [[M-Flo]]'s [[Taku Takahashi]] and features rapper [[Verbal (rapper)|Verbal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DJ Hello Kitty and Ayumi Hamasaki United at Last!|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2013-10-25/dj-hello-kitty-and-ayumi-hamasaki-united-at-last|publisher=Anime News Network|accessdate=16 January 2014|date=25 December 2013}}</ref> Both songs are heavily influenced by Western [[dance-pop]] music.

===2014&ndash;2015: ''Colours'', ''A One'', ''Sixxxxxx''===
In January 2014, it was announced that a new song entitled "Pray" was chosen to be the theme song for the anime film ''[[Buddha (manga)#Anime films|Osamu Tezuka's Budda 2—Owarinaki Tabi]]'', which premiered on February 8, 2014 in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|title=浜崎あゆみ、新曲「Pray」がアニメ映画『BUDDHA2』主題歌に決定|url=http://www.excite.co.jp/News/music/20131021/Musicman_artist29985.html|publisher=Excite News|accessdate=15 June 2014|language=Japanese}}</ref> The song was released digitally on January 27, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=新曲「Pray」配信スタート!!|url=http://avex.jp/ayu/news/detail.php?id=1006654|website=Ayumi Hamasaki Official website|accessdate=15 June 2014|language=Japanese}}</ref> Another new song, entitled "Hello New Me", was presented as theme song for a new season of Fuji TV drama ''[[Saigo Kara Nibanme no Koi|Zoku—Saigo Kara Nibanme no Koi]].'' which started broadcasting in April, 2014. The song was released digitally on May 14, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=浜崎あゆみ、ドラマ主題歌の新曲「Hello new me」iTunesで配信開始 |url=http://yukan-news.ameba.jp/20140516-110/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140516010101/http://yukan-news.ameba.jp/20140516-110/ |website=Ameba News |accessdate=15 June 2014 |archivedate=May 16, 2014 |dead-url=yes |language=Japanese |df= }}</ref> From May 30 to July 6, 2014, Hamasaki held her ''Premium Showcase: Feel the love'' tour, on which she offered 11 concerts at 3 locations: Nagoya, Osaka and Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web|title=LIVE - "ayumi hamasaki PREMIUM SHOWCASE ～Feel the love～"|url=http://avex.jp/ayu/live/tour.php?id=1000145|website=Ayumi Hamasaki Official website|accessdate=15 June 2014|language=Japanese}}</ref> On this tour Hamasaki abandoned for the first time the traditional format of her previous concerts and presented a uninterrupted, shorter show, on which she also debuted as an [[Aerial silk|aerial acrobat]].<ref>{{cite web|title=【ライブレポート】浜崎あゆみ、ショーケースライブで魅せる。危険と隣り合わせのフライング - 浜崎あゆみ - BARKS音楽ニュース|url=http://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000105302|website=Barks Ongaku News|accessdate=3 December 2014|language=Japanese|date=3 July 2014}}</ref> Hamasaki's fifteenth studio album, entitled ''[[Colours (Ayumi Hamasaki album)|Colours]]'', was released on July 2, 2014. The album featured internationally renowned producers, such as [[RedOne]], [[Rodney Jerkins]], [[Armin van Buuren]] and [[Fedde le Grand]], making the first time in Hamasaki's career in which primarily Western producers were appointed to produce one of her studio albums.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayumi Hamasaki's New Challenge, the "Premium Showcase"|url=http://www.en.barks.jp/news/?id=1000004597|publisher=Barks|accessdate=23 April 2014|date=17 April 2014}}</ref> ''Colours'' peaked at number five on its first week on the Oricon charts, becoming Hamasaki's first studio album to debut out of the Top 3. However, it also marked a new record for her, as with this achievement she became the second artist in Japan's history—after [[Yumi Matsutoya]]—to have 47 of her albums within the Top 10 of the charts.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:浜崎あゆみ、松任谷由実と並び歴代1位に「アルバムトップ10獲得数」記録で |url=http://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20140710-00010004-musicv-ent |website=Yahoo Japan News |accessdate=14 July 2014 |language=Japanese |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715194852/http://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20140710-00010004-musicv-ent |archivedate=July 15, 2014 |df= }}</ref> In September 2014, Hamasaki released two recut singles from ''Colours'': "[[Terminal (Ayumi Hamasaki song)|Terminal]]" and "XOXO" on the [[Machine Shop Recordings#PlugAir|PlugAir]] platform. The single was released under [[Linkin Park]]'s [[Machine Shop Recordings|Machine Shop Records]] for the American release.<ref>[http://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000107521 Hamasaki Ayumi releases her two singles "Terminal" and "XOXO" on the PlugAir platform.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041425/http://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000107521 |date=March 4, 2016 }} ''Barks Japan'' September 18, 2014.</ref>

On October 18, 2014, Hamasaki performed as the closing act in the [[A-Nation]] premium concert held at the [[Marina Bay Sands]]’ MasterCard Theatres in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayumi Hamasaki brings the house down at a-nation Singapore |url=http://www.msn.com/en-ph/news/entertainment-celebrity/ayumi-hamasaki-brings-the-house-down-at-a-nation-singapore/ss-BB9S5Hj#image=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019010101/http://www.msn.com/en-ph/news/entertainment-celebrity/ayumi-hamasaki-brings-the-house-down-at-a-nation-singapore/ss-BB9S5Hj |website=MSN Philippines News |publisher=MSN |accessdate=19 October 2014 |dead-url=yes |archivedate=October 19, 2014 |df= }}</ref> This was the second time performing in Singapore after her [[MTV Asia Awards 2002|MTV Asia Awards]] performance 12 years ago. On November 2, 2014, Hamasaki announced through her official Facebook page that she had started recording new material composed by Tetsuya Komuro, Kunio Tago and Tetsuya Yukumi for a "winter ballad trilogy" [[extended play|single]].<ref>{{cite web|title=(no title)|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=919519621399494&id=250061788345284|website=Ayumi Hamasaki official Facebook page|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=3 November 2014|date=2 November 2014}}</ref> On November 6, 2014, the title of the single was revealed to be "Zutto.../Last Minute/Walk", and its release date was set for December 24, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=クリスマス・イヴに贈るayuのバラード3部作、12月24日リリース！ NEW SINGLE「Zutto... / Last minute / Walk」|url=http://avex.jp/ayu/discography/detail.php?id=1009092|website=Ayumi Hamasaki Official website|accessdate=7 November 2014|date=6 November 2014}}</ref> On November 10, 2014, it was announced that Hamasaki would be collaborating in a tribute [[Cover version#Tributes, tribute albums and cover albums|cover album]] for [[Hikaru Utada]], entitled ''Utada Hikaru no Uta'', to be released on December 9, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=ayumi hamasaki will be a part of a Hikaru Utada cover album ''Utada Hikaru No Uta -13kumino Ongakukaniyoru 13nokaisyakunitsuite-'' which will be released on December 9th!!|url=https://www.facebook.com/ayu.official|website=Ayumi Hamasaki official Facebook page|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=14 November 2014|date=10 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=林檎、陽水、靖幸、ayu、ミリヤら宇多田ヒカル楽曲カバー|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/130923|publisher=Natalie.mu|accessdate=14 November 2014|language=Japanese|date=11 November 2014}}</ref> For the album she contributed with a cover of Utada's 1998 single "[[Movin' on Without You]]", which was arranged by the RedOne production team.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:宇多田ヒカルのうた』全貌明らかに。井上陽水、椎名林檎、浜崎あゆみ、吉井和哉ら参加アーティストコメント|url=http://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000110305|website=Barks Ongaku News|accessdate=2 December 2014|language=Japanese}}</ref> The winter ballad trilogy single, "[[Zutto.../Last Minute/Walk]]", was released on December 24, 2014, and peaked at number five on the Oricon charts. With this achievement, Hamasaki became the first solo artist in Japan's history to have 50 singles within the Top 10 of the Oricon charts. As for artists in general, Hamasaki became the third artist with more Top ten singles since Oricon's foundation in 1968—being surpassed by groups [[Morning Musume]] and [[SMAP]], with 57 and 53 Top ten singles respectively<ref>{{cite web|title=浜崎あゆみ、ソロ史上初のシングル50作TOP10入り|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2046654/full/|publisher=Oricon|accessdate=2 January 2015|language=Japanese|date=30 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=浜崎あゆみ、史上初のシングル50作TOP10入り。クラシック・アルバム『LOVE CLASSICS』詳細も|url=http://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000111238|website=Barks|accessdate=2 January 2015|language=Japanese|date=30 December 2014}}</ref> In December 2014 Hamasaki announced that she would be not attending the New Year show [[Kōhaku Uta Gassen]] for the first time in 15 years. She explained her decision stating that she wanted to lower her responsibilities and things she felt pressured to do, in order to focus on the projects she had for her career, mainly regarding her plans to expand her influence throughout Asia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayumi Hamasaki to skip 'Kohaku Uta Gassen' for first time in 15 years|url=http://www.japantoday.com/category/entertainment/view/ayumi-hamasaki-to-skip-kohaku-uta-gassen-for-first-time-in-15-years|website=Japan Today|accessdate=14 January 2015|date=28 November 2014}}</ref>

On February 15, 2015, Hamasaki made a surprise guest appearance during Singaporean singer [[JJ Lin]]'s concert in Taipei, Taiwan. They performed a duet version of Hamasaki's 2000 single "[[Seasons (Ayumi Hamasaki song)|Seasons]]", and announced that JJ Lin would be producing a song for Hamasaki's next studio album, ''[[A One (album)|A One]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayumi Hamasaki’s first Taiwan visit in seven years. Surprise appearance at JJ Lin’s Taipei Arena concert|url=http://www.en.barks.jp/news/?id=1000005316|website=Barks}}</ref> The album was released on April 8, 2015, including singles "Zutto...", "Last Minute", "Walk", Utada's cover "Movin' on Without You", and JJ Lin-produced song "The Gift", for which a promotional music video was also made. Between April and July 2015, Hamasaki embarked on her ''Arena Tour 2015 A Cirque de Minuit'' tour throughout Japan, which was planned as an expanded version of her previous Countdown Live concerts held in late 2014. The tour consisted of a 34-song setlist show with a duration of 3 hours and 45 minutes, her longest concert held to date.<ref>{{cite web|title=浜崎あゆみ史上最長3時間45分、徹底演出で魅せた"真夜中のサーカス"|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/152944|website=Natalie.mu|accessdate=2 January 2016|language=Japanese}}</ref> At the final show of the aforementioned tour, Hamasaki announced that she would start another tour in September, this time exclusively for members of her official fan club, TeamAyu. The ''TA Limited Live Tour'', Hamasaki's first fan club exclusive tour in twelve years after 2003, began on September 29, 2015 and included a total of 16 concerts at 7 venues.<ref>{{cite web|title=2015年秋、TA LIMITED LIVE TOUR　開催決定！！|url=http://avex.jp/ayu/news/detail.php?id=1024164|website=Ayumi Hamasaki Official Website|accessdate=2 January 2016|language=Japanese}}</ref>

In April 2015, a new song entitled "Step by Step" began to be broadcast as the theme song of NHK TV drama ''Bijo to Danshi'', and was subsequently released as a digital single on July 1.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayumi Hamasaki will release new song, "Step by step", as digital single|url=http://www.en.barks.jp/news/?id=1000005683|website=Barks|accessdate=6 December 2015}}</ref> On August 5, 2015, Hamasaki released her sixth extended play, entitled ''[[Sixxxxxx]]''. The mini album featured six new songs, including drama theme song "Step by Step", and "Sayonara", a new song featuring Taiwanese boyband SpeXial.<ref>{{cite web|title=Amazon.co.jp: 浜崎あゆみ : sixxxxxx【CD＋Blu-ray】 - 音楽|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/exec/obidos/ASIN/B00VYQ7QUG/nataliemusic-22|website=Amazon.co.jp|accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref> "Sayonara" became #1 on digital downloads charts in Taiwan, Hong Kong, Singapore and Malaysia, according to KK BOX, Asia’s largest digital distribution site.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayumi Hamasaki x SpeXial Collab Dominates Weekly Charts in Taiwan, Hong Kong, Singapore and Malaysia|url=http://www.mtv81.com/news/ayumi-hamasaki-x-spexial-collab-dominates-weekly-charts-in-taiwan-hong-kong-singapore-and-malaysia/|website=MTV 81|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref> In addition, Hamasaki participated as one of the headliners of the [[A-Nation|A-Nation Stadium Fes 2015]] held on August 30 at the [[Ajinomoto Stadium]], where she also performed a cover of [[Globe (band)|Globe]]'s hit ballad song "Departures", joined by Tetsuya Komuro and Naoya Urata onstage.<ref>{{cite web|title=ayu、TRF、EXOら熱演で「a-nation stadium fes.」大団円|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/158786|website=Natalie.mu|accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref> She also recorded a cover of Globe's "Many Classic Moments", which was included in the group's tribute album released on December 16, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=globeカバー盤にHYDE、浜崎あゆみ、NMB梅田ら追加＆曲目判明|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/168086|website=Natalie.mu|accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref> On December 23, 2015, Hamasaki released a winter-themed concept album entitled ''[[Winter Diary: A7 Classical]]'', which included songs from her previous two albums -''A One'' and -''Sixxxxxx''- remixed with [[Classical music|Classical]] arrangements, and one new song "Winter Diary", which was produced by Tetsuya Komuro.<ref>{{cite web|title=浜崎あゆみ冬のクラシック盤、小室哲哉と美人すぎるバイオリニスト参加|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/166986|website=Natalie.mu|accessdate=2 January 2016}}</ref> Hamasaki promoted the album by starting an [[Instagram]] account that would be active for only a month until the end of January 2016.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hamasaki, Ayumi|title=Ayumi Hamasaki's Official Instagram|url=https://www.instagram.com/a.you/|website=[[Instagram]]|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref> She shared pictures of the music video shooting of "Winter Diary" recorded in Taiwan, and also the preparations for her 2015-2016 countdown live concerts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hamasaki Ayumi launches Instagram account for a limited time|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2015/12/hamasaki-ayumi-launches-instagram-account-for-a-limited-time|website=Tokyo Hive|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>

In December 2015, Hamasaki also contributed with the lyrics of "Diary", the debut single of fellow artist Micchie, who has been working as one of her live band's back-up singers since 2011. The lyrics "Diary" were credited to CREA, and the song was composed by Timothy Wellard, who's also been contributing as part of Hamasaki's live band and composing music for her since 2011. Micchie's single was released on December 23, 2015, through [[Nippon Crown]].<ref>{{cite news |title=miccie、浜崎あゆみツアーで披露した「Diary」を配信リリース |url=https://www.barks.jp/news/?id=1000122664 |accessdate=17 July 2018 |publisher=Barks Japan Music Network |date=23 December 2015 |language=Japanese}}</ref>

===2016: ''Made in Japan''===
On her last Instagram post, Hamasaki confirmed that she has been working on her seventeenth studio album for 2016.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hamasaki, Ayumi|title=Heard that today n tmrw will b snowy days so I changed my plans and just started working on my new album at home |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BA4eurHJPlt/|website=Instagram|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref> A 15th anniversary edition of Hamasaki's 2001 [[greatest hits album]] ''[[A Best]]'' was released on March 28, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=『A(ロゴ) BEST -15th Anniversary Edition-』|url=http://avex.jp/ayu/news/detail.php?id=1031568|website=Ayumi Hamasaki official website|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref> In May 2016, Hamasaki started her nationwide tour ''Arena Tour 2016 A: Made in Japan'', which will be an expanded version of her 2015-2016 Countdown Live ''Made in Tokyo''.<ref>{{cite web|title=『“ayumi hamasaki ARENA TOUR 2016 A(ロゴ) ～MADE IN JAPAN～”』開催大決定！！|url=http://avex.jp/ayu/news/detail.php?id=1031561|website=Ayumi Hamasaki official website|accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref> On May 11, Hamasaki made a surprise release of her 17th studio album, entitled ''Made in Japan'', through music streaming website AWA, where it reached 1 million legal streams after 5 days of release.<ref>{{cite web|title=BIG NEWS!! 「AWA」にて、6月29日発売のニューアルバム「M(A)DE IN JAPAN」が、CD発売の1ヶ月半前の5月11日(水)より全曲独占先行配信決定!!|url=http://avex.jp/ayu/news/detail.php?id=1035694|website=Ayumi Hamasaki official website|accessdate=15 May 2016|language=Japanese|date=11 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=浜崎あゆみ再生100万回、新アルバム先行配信|url=http://www.nikkansports.com/entertainment/news/1653144.html|website=Nikkan Sports|accessdate=28 May 2016|language=Japanese}}</ref> The album is set to be released on physical formats on June 29, 2016. With the album peaking at number two on the weekly [[Oricon]] chart, Hamasaki became the solo-artist with the most top-ten albums (50).<ref>http://music-book.jp/music/news/news/120810</ref>

On September 30, 2016, Hamasaki released the digital single "We are the Queens", which was used as a theme song of smartphone game ''Clash of Queens'' developed by Elex Wireless. Hamasaki herself starred in the TV commercial for the game, which was first broadcast on September 17.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayumi Hamasaki Assumes Rightful Role as Queen in new CMs; new song "We are the QUEENS"|url=http://aramajapan.com/news/newrelease/ayumi-hamasaki-assumes-rightful-role-as-queen-in-new-cms-new-song-we-are-the-queens/64050/|website=Arama Japan|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref>

On September 6, 2017, Hamasaki released a new song entitled "Words" as a free download for attenders to her ''Just the Beginning: Sacrifice'' tour, available until November 30 through website [[mu-mo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ayumi hamasaki 来場者限定｢WORDS｣ダウンロードサイト |url=http://sp-m.mu-mo.net/specials/sp/ayu1709/index.html|website=mu-mo|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>

During 2017 Hamasaki embarked on her ''Just the Beginning -20- Tour 2017'', whose first leg started on May 13, 2017 at Yokohama Arena through July 17 at the Osaka-jō Hall, Osaka. The second leg of the tour, entitled ''Just the beginning Part 2: Sacrifice'', commenced on September 6 at the Pacifico Yokohama National Convention Hall, Yokohama, and is scheduled to end on November 28 at the Shunanshi Bunka Hall, Yamaguchi. A third leg of the tour has also been scheduled, starting on December 2, 2017 at the Wakayama Prefectural Cultural Hall, through February 20, 2018, at the Okinawa Convention Center.<ref>{{cite web|title=ayumi hamasaki Just the beginning -20- TOUR 2017|url=http://avex.jp/ayu/live/tour.php?id=1001001|website=Ayumi Hamasaki official website|publisher=Avex|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref>

===2018: 20th anniversary, "Trouble"===
From April 7, 2018 to July 22, 2018, Hamasaki embarked on her arena tour titled Power of Music, in celebration of her 20th anniversary.<ref>https://aramajapan.com/news/ayumi-kicks-off-20th-anniversary-arena-tour/84462/</ref>

In July 2018, Hamasaki participated in a special concert alongside the likes of Crystal Kay, Daichi Miura, LiSA, as well as King & Prince.<ref>https://aramajapan.com/aramaexclusive/featured/ayumi-hamasaki-arashi-crystal-kay-daichi-miura-and-more-perform-on-2018-fns-uta-no-natsu-matsuri/90154/</ref> Later that same month, she announced the release of her seventh extended play, [[Trouble (Ayumi Hamasaki EP)|TROUBLE]], which was released on August 15, 2018.<ref>https://aramajapan.com/news/newrelease/ayumi-hamasaki-to-release-new-album-trouble-in-august-2018/90108/</ref>

==Image and artistry==
[[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]] has noted that Hamasaki lacked talents such as the dance moves of [[Namie Amuro]], the "supermodel allure" of [[Hitomi (singer)|Hitomi]], and the "vocal pyrotechnics" of [[Hikaru Utada]]. Her own fans even considered her high-pitched voice screechy.<ref name="SinChew" /><ref name="Time2" /> However, her music is sometimes considered one of the major forces in shaping Japan's current music trends; this has been attributed to her constantly changing image as well as her self-penned lyrics,<ref name="SinChew" /> though critics credit clever marketing strategies.<ref name="Metropolis"/><ref name="SinChew"/><ref name="Time2"/> Hamasaki is also noted for the visual aspects of her artistry: she is considered a fashion trendsetter, with her influence extending beyond Japan.<ref name="time_photoessay2">{{cite news|first=Lisa |last=Takeuchi Cullen |url=http://www.time.com/time/asia/features/ayumi_hamasaki/photoessay/2.html |title=The Many Faces of Ayu |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=May 3, 2008 |page=2 |date=March 25, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415191511/http://www.time.com/time/asia/features/ayumi_hamasaki/photoessay/2.html |archivedate=April 15, 2008 |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name="time3">{{cite news|first=Lisa |last=Takeuchi Cullen |url=http://www.time.com/time/asia/features/ayumi_hamasaki/photoessay/3.html |title=The Many Faces of Ayu |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=May 3, 2008 |page=3 |date=March 25, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415191516/http://www.time.com/time/asia/features/ayumi_hamasaki/photoessay/3.html |archivedate=April 15, 2008 |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name="washingtonpost">{{cite news| last = Pan| first = Philip P.|work=Washington Post| title=Taiwan's Teens Take Style Cues From Tokyo| date=November 27, 2000}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' says that Hamasaki has "married accessible, mainstream hits with over-the-top costumes and high-concept videos".<ref>{{cite news|last=Nieman|first=Teresa|title=Why Japanese Pop Matters|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/mar/25/japanese-pop-women|accessdate=August 31, 2010|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=March 25, 2010}}</ref> The widespread influence of her music and her constantly changing image has meant that Hamasaki has often been compared to [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].<ref>{{cite news| last=Hickey | first= David| url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fm20060622a1.html | title= The D.I.Y. Route to Rock Stardom|work=The Japan Times | date=June 22, 2006|accessdate=February 5, 2009}}</ref><ref name="AyuFaces6">"{{cite news|first=Lisa |last=Takeuchi Cullen |url=http://www.time.com/time/asia/features/ayumi_hamasaki/photoessay/6.html |title=The Many Faces of Ayu |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=February 2, 2008 |page=6 |date=March 25, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215041611/http://www.time.com/time/asia/features/ayumi_hamasaki/photoessay/6.html |archivedate=December 15, 2007 |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref>

Hamasaki's lyrics and image have gained a following predominantly among the [[Generation X]] of Asia, mainly because of the "conflicting or inharmonious beauty" of her fashion and lyrics; Hamasaki's fashions combine Eastern and Western elements, and her songs, unlike those of many of her contemporaries, mostly all have English titles but contained no English lyrics (until ''Rainbow'').<ref name="SinChew" /> Music critic Tetsu Misaki believed that the juxtaposition of her fashionable appearance and her personal lyrics was one of her most important selling points.<ref name="Jpopnonihongo1">{{cite book |author=Misaki, Tetsu |chapter=浜崎あゆみ～共感はどこまで可能か |trans-chapter=Ayumi Hamasaki: How far can empathy go? |title=Jポップの日本語―歌詞論 |trans-title=J-Pop Japanese: Lyricism |language=Japanese |location=[[Chiyoda, Tokyo]] |publisher=Sairyuusha |publication-date=July 20, 2002 |pages=23–40 |asin= |bibcode= |isbn=4-88202-752-6}}</ref> The popularity of her music extends beyond Japan;<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-20827647_ITM | title=Viacom's MTV Networks Announces Landmark Content and Advertising Alliance with China's No. 1 Search Engine Baidu. | date=October 17, 2006 | publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|accessdate=February 5, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090111232012/http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-20827647_ITM| archivedate= January 11, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> she has a "sizable [following] across Asia" and is one of the few Japanese singers whose albums have sold over 10,000 copies in Singapore.<ref>{{cite news| publisher = [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]| url=http://www.star-ecentral.com/news/story.asp?file=/2006/1/9/music/13031077&sec=music| title=Discovering Fujita| date=January 9, 2006|accessdate=February 5, 2009| archiveurl= https://archive.is/20090109060610/http://www.star-ecentral.com/news/story.asp?file=/2006/1/9/music/13031077&sec=music| archivedate= January 9, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first=Brian| last=Bremner|work=BusinessWeek| url=http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/may2007/gb20070507_535989.htm| title=Raising Japan's Cool Quotient| date=May 7, 2007|accessdate=February 5, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090304031415/http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/may2007/gb20070507_535989.htm| archivedate= March 4, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> In 2002, however, Hamasaki's domestic sales began declining due to a sluggish Japanese market and increasing [[copyright infringement|piracy]] in Japan.<ref name="Time4" /> As a result, she began moving toward the Asian market in 2002, performing at the 2002 MTV Asia awards in Singapore, at South Korea's "[[Asia Song Festival]]", and at a concert in Beijing to celebrate [[Sino-Japanese relations]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-5231327_ITM |title=Asian Stars to Shine in Seoul. |date=November 26, 2004 |publisher=[[Yonhap]] |accessdate=August 5, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207161403/http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-5231327_ITM |archivedate=December 7, 2008 }} (Registration needed to view article)</ref><ref>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ZrKnkRHv?url=http://archive.japantoday.com/jp/news/233912 |archivedate=August 6, 2008 |url=http://archive.japantoday.com/jp/news/233912 |title=Japan, China celebrate 30 years with gala concert |first=Sachie |last=Kanda |date=October 10, 2002 |publisher=[[Japan Today]] |accessdate=August 5, 2008 |deadurl=yes |df=mdy }}</ref> With her popularity declining (due in part to the rising popularity of other singers), she made a foray into the Asian market, starting with her first tour of Asia in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=She goes all out to charm Hong Kong |url=http://newpaper.asia1.com.sg/show/story/0,4136,132975,00.html |work=[[The New Paper]] |publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]] |date=June 12, 2007 |accessdate=February 4, 2009 |first=James |last=Kang |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616060521/http://newpaper.asia1.com.sg/show/story/0%2C4136%2C132975%2C00.html |archivedate=June 16, 2007 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>

===Musical style===
{{quote box
| quote = In the beginning, I was searching for myself in my music. My music was for me. I didn't have the mental room to be conscious of the listener; I wrote to save myself. I didn't understand what it was to write songs. But over time I began to see many things, my influence, the responsibilities that gave me.
| source = — Hamasaki on the new lyrical directions in ''I Am...''.<ref name="TimeInterview"/>
| width = 30%
| salign = right
}}
Hamasaki's lyrics, all her own,{{refn|Two of Hamasaki's songs released prior to ''Rainbow'', "[[Love (Destiny)|Love: Since 1999]]" and "[[Audience (Ayumi Hamasaki song)|Audience]]" used English. However, the lyrics of "Love (Since 1999)" were not written by Hamasaki, and the only English in "Audience" is the word "yes"; therefore these songs are usually not counted among her songs using English.<ref name="Time4">{{cite news|last=Takeuchi Cullen |first=Lisa |url=http://www.time.com/time/asia/features/ayumi_hamasaki/cover4.html |title=Empress of Pop |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=March 31, 2008 |page=4 |date=March 25, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080322074147/http://www.time.com/time/asia/features/ayumi_hamasaki/cover4.html |archivedate=March 22, 2008 |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref>|group=fn|name="lyrics"
}} have resonated among her fans, who praise them as being honest and heartfelt and "expressing determination"; in two surveys conducted by Oricon, respondents voted Hamasaki's lyrics as their favorite aspect of her artistry.<ref name="10thoricon"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/music/special/070228_01.html|title=A Thorough Analysis! Her Best-of Albums and Approaching Her Charm! |last=Yuuki|first=Tai|date=February 28, 2007|work=[[Oricon Style]]|publisher=[[Oricon]]|accessdate=November 3, 2009}}</ref> Steve McClure of ''[[The Japan Times]]'' noted that Hamasaki has "developed a reputation as a thoughtful, introspective lyricist"; Barry Walters of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' comments that Hamasaki's lyrics "pack unlikely insights".<ref name="VillageVoice" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fm20011219a1.html|title=2001 – A Sound Odyssey|last=McClure|first=Steve|date=December 19, 2001|work=The Japan Times |publisher=The Japan Times Ltd.|accessdate=November 4, 2009}}</ref> Having "trouble voicing her thoughts", Hamasaki uses her lyrics as an outlet; she draws inspiration from her own (and occasionally her friends') experiences and emotions and tries to put them "honestly into words".<ref name="AvexProfile" /> She has stated that honesty is essential to her lyrics, saying, "If I write when I'm low, it will be a dark song, but I don't care. I want to be honest with myself at all times."<ref name="AvexProfile">{{cite web | url=http://www.avexnet.or.jp/english/ayu/#profile | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051217103237/http://www.avexnet.or.jp/english/ayu/#profile | archivedate=December 17, 2005 | title=Ayumi Hamasaki's Profile (Avex)| publisher=[[Avex Trax|Avex Network]]| accessdate=March 23, 2008}}</ref> This meant that she did not use English lyrics until her album ''Rainbow'', as she felt that she could best express herself in Japanese.<ref group=fn name="lyrics" /> As with her musical style, the themes of her lyrics have varied. Her debut album ''A Song for ××'' dealt mostly with themes of "loneliness and confusion", as did her second album ''Loveppears''. ''Duty'' likewise expressed feelings of disappointment and confusion. Hamasaki began to take on a more global outlook with her following albums ''I Am...'' and ''Rainbow'', branching out to wider themes such as faith and peace.<ref name="Time5"/> Music critic Tetsu Misaki noted a large change in her lyrics style between her debut album ''A Song for ××'' (1999), which mostly dealt with personal problems, and her following albums ''Loveppears'' and ''Duty''. Misaki believed Hamasaki had begun thinking about her influence on society more, and began writing songs with important messages she wanted to express to her listeners. This was signalled by her not using first person pronouns as much, and instead using the words {{nihongo|''bokura''|僕ら||"we"}} and {{nihongo|''tsutaeru''|伝える||"convey"}} more often.<ref name="Jpopnonihongo1"/> As Hamasaki matured, her lyrics began to express more confidence; themes in her later albums included love and the struggles of women.<ref name="rainbow"/><ref name="Sweet">{{cite magazine| title=Ayumi Hamasaki | magazine=Sweet |date=January 2006|pages=18–20|author=Hayakawa, Kanako|language=ja}}</ref><ref name="vivi"/> With ''Guilty'', Hamasaki began to compose her lyrics not only as an exposition of her personal feelings but as encouragements for her listeners, an outlook she applied in ''Next Level'' as well. In songs such as "Talkin' 2 Myself" and "Mirrorcle World", Hamasaki deals with the "awareness and fighting spirit of surviving in a high-risk age" to encourage listeners; in "Rollin'" (from ''Next Level''), Hamasaki writes, "The age is rolling around/At the speed of heading toward the end/Beyond the border/Disappointment and hope fight with each other".<ref>{{cite news|last=Fuji |first=Miho |title=Ayumi Hamasaki 『NEXT LEVEL』 |url=http://www.tokyoheadline.com/vol402/show01.html |accessdate=September 2, 2010 |newspaper=[[Tokyo Headline]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313063846/http://www.tokyoheadline.com/vol402/show01.html |archivedate=March 13, 2012 }}</ref> In addition to personal experiences and feelings, Hamasaki bases lyrics on sources such as historical events. The life of [[Joan of Arc]] was the inspiration for "[[Free & Easy (Ayumi Hamasaki song)|Free & Easy]]", while a story told to her by her friend about a [[saint]] named Mary served as the basis for "M"; the [[September 11 attacks]] inspired "A Song Is Born".<ref name=autogenerated1>''J-Point''. December 22, 2000. Volume 75.</ref><ref name=joanofarc>{{cite news|url=http://www.epochtimes.com/b5/2/4/19/n184448.htm|title=Ayumi Hamasaki Most Recently Models as Joan of Arc|newspaper=[[The Epoch Times]]|accessdate=January 26, 2009|date=April 19, 2002| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090306222030/http://www.epochtimes.com/b5/2/4/19/n184448.htm| archivedate= March 6, 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no|language=zh}}</ref>
