[[File:Harry Been (1989).jpg|thumb|Harry Been (1989)]] '''Harry Been''' (born 1949) is a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] businessman who presided over the organizing committees of [[Euro 2000]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.soccertimes.com/international/2000/jun18.htm|title=England threatened with expulsion if hooligans are not restrained.|date=18 June 2000|work=Soccertimes|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref> the [[2005 FIFA World Youth Championship]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=104/edition=9102/news/newsid=98996.html|title=Blatter: Bravo to the organisers|date=1 July 2005|work=fifa.com|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref> and the [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/news/newsid=552685.html|title=Under-21s set for thrilling finale|last=Chaplin|first=Mark|date=19 June 2007|work=uefa.com|publisher=[[UEFA]]|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref> He is head of the joint [[Netherlands]] and [[Belgium]] bid to host the [[2018 FIFA World Cup bids|2018 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sport.scotsman.com/world-cup/World-Cup-winners-will-net.5883942.jp|title=World Cup winners will net £19million reward|last=Johnson|first=Phil|date=4 December 2009|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref>
Harry Been is also known for his controversial decision to ask the continuation of the UEFA 2016 game between Serbia and Albania, after hooligan fans entered the pitch and physically attacked Albanian players.
